{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_end","contentIndex":1,"toolCall":{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2183","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves by preponderance that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure. NOTAM A1010/26 (May 22-25) suspended all civil flight permits in western Tehran FIR, closed all airports in that major region except limited daylight operations with fresh CAA approval, suspended previous permissions, and was security-related. This satisfies the rule's 'broad closure...suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from... a major Iranian airspace region' with permitted limited exceptions.\"}"}},"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on my review of the admitted evidence and the arbitration record, I need to make my determination. The key issue is whether the evidence demonstrates by a preponderance that Iran initiated a \"major closure\" of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\n\nThe market rule defines a \"major closure\" as:\n1. A broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region\n2. OR a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports\n3. Limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure\n\nThe evidence shows:\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, 2026, valid until May 25, 2026 (covering the May 24 deadline)\n- The NOTAM closed \"all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR\" except listed airports\n- All previous permissions were suspended and new CAA permission was required for civil IFR passenger flights\n- The restrictions were security-related (non-weather) as confirmed by EASA CZIB\n- Contemporaneous reports (Indian Express, RFE/RL) corroborate the restrictions and their scope\n\nThe defense argues this is merely airport operations restrictions, not a broad airspace closure. However, the rule's definition includes \"suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from... a major Iranian airspace region.\" The western Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region, and the NOTAM's effect was to broadly suspend commercial aviation operations in that region, with only limited exceptions requiring fresh CAA approval.\n\nThe evidence demonstrates by a preponderance that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace by the deadline."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2183","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves by preponderance that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure. NOTAM A1010/26 (May 22-25) suspended all civil flight permits in western Tehran FIR, closed all airports in that major region except limited daylight operations with fresh CAA approval, suspended previous permissions, and was security-related. This satisfies the rule's 'broad closure...suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from... a major Iranian airspace region' with permitted limited exceptions.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":1728,"output":511,"cacheRead":51328,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":53567,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782828955181,"responseId":"gen-1782828955-TWKa46bPggimynBJq7lO"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on my review of the admitted evidence and the arbitration record, I need to make my determination. The key issue is whether the evidence demonstrates by a preponderance that Iran initiated a \"major closure\" of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\n\nThe market rule defines a \"major closure\" as:\n1. A broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region\n2. OR a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports\n3. Limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure\n\nThe evidence shows:\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, 2026, valid until May 25, 2026 (covering the May 24 deadline)\n- The NOTAM closed \"all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR\" except listed airports\n- All previous permissions were suspended and new CAA permission was required for civil IFR passenger flights\n- The restrictions were security-related (non-weather) as confirmed by EASA CZIB\n- Contemporaneous reports (Indian Express, RFE/RL) corroborate the restrictions and their scope\n\nThe defense argues this is merely airport operations restrictions, not a broad airspace closure. However, the rule's definition includes \"suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from... a major Iranian airspace region.\" The western Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region, and the NOTAM's effect was to broadly suspend commercial aviation operations in that region, with only limited exceptions requiring fresh CAA approval.\n\nThe evidence demonstrates by a preponderance that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace by the deadline."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2183","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves by preponderance that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure. NOTAM A1010/26 (May 22-25) suspended all civil flight permits in western Tehran FIR, closed all airports in that major region except limited daylight operations with fresh CAA approval, suspended previous permissions, and was security-related. This satisfies the rule's 'broad closure...suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from... a major Iranian airspace region' with permitted limited exceptions.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":1728,"output":511,"cacheRead":51328,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":53567,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782828955181,"responseId":"gen-1782828955-TWKa46bPggimynBJq7lO"}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on my review of the admitted evidence and the arbitration record, I need to make my determination. The key issue is whether the evidence demonstrates by a preponderance that Iran initiated a \"major closure\" of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\n\nThe market rule defines a \"major closure\" as:\n1. A broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region\n2. OR a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports\n3. Limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure\n\nThe evidence shows:\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, 2026, valid until May 25, 2026 (covering the May 24 deadline)\n- The NOTAM closed \"all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR\" except listed airports\n- All previous permissions were suspended and new CAA permission was required for civil IFR passenger flights\n- The restrictions were security-related (non-weather) as confirmed by EASA CZIB\n- Contemporaneous reports (Indian Express, RFE/RL) corroborate the restrictions and their scope\n\nThe defense argues this is merely airport operations restrictions, not a broad airspace closure. However, the rule's definition includes \"suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from... a major Iranian airspace region.\" The western Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region, and the NOTAM's effect was to broadly suspend commercial aviation operations in that region, with only limited exceptions requiring fresh CAA approval.\n\nThe evidence demonstrates by a preponderance that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace by the deadline."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2183","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves by preponderance that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure. NOTAM A1010/26 (May 22-25) suspended all civil flight permits in western Tehran FIR, closed all airports in that major region except limited daylight operations with fresh CAA approval, suspended previous permissions, and was security-related. This satisfies the rule's 'broad closure...suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from... a major Iranian airspace region' with permitted limited exceptions.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":1728,"output":511,"cacheRead":51328,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":53567,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782828955181,"responseId":"gen-1782828955-TWKa46bPggimynBJq7lO"}}
